<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-440-729  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 440 729.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 10 1990 v9 n19 p72(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army gets kudos for $700M award without a protest. (Fedwatch)(column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Electronic Data Systems Corp. (contracts).andO;Topic:     United States. ArmyDefense ContractsInformation SystemsCompetitionUnited States. General Accounting OfficeUnited States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppeals.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army Gets Kudos For $700M Award Without a ProtestandM;Kudos are due when agencies avoid protests.andP;  Something strange happened, ordidn't happen, last month.andP;  In a rare occurrence, a large indefinite-deliverycontract was awarded without a protest.andM;Apparently the Army, in awarding the Small Multiuser Contract for $700million to Electronic Data Systems Corp., did such a good job that none ofthe other bidders could find even the slightest flaw.andP;  We all know howeagerly the press jumps all over agencies when protests are lodged, so it isequally appropriate to acknowledge a job well done.andM;The losing vendors I talked to agree that the Army's conduct was good,including a very thorough debriefing.andP;  There was an earlier protest duringthe procurement alleging restrictive specifications, but that was resolved.andM;And there was that embarassing glitch when the Army sent a proprietarydocument to the wrong vendor.andM;Considering all the pitfalls of a large procurement, it is a wonder to beholdwhen no protest is lodged.andP;  Congratulations to the Army.andM;As I track the protest scene, I have compiled some interesting statistics onthe relative success rate of protests at the General Services AdministrationBoard of Contract Appeals and the General Accounting Office.andP;  Over the last3-1/2 years, at GSBCA about 50 percent of unsettled protests were successful.andO;About two-thirds of all protests are settled before the hearing because ofthe high cost of this process.andM;For information technology-related protests, the story is quite different atGAO.andP;  The success rate has been about 18 percent from 1987 to 1989, with anintriguing upturn in the first half of 1990 to 36 percent.andP;  This increase maybe an aberration, or it may show the results of a change in attitude inprotest resolution.andP;  I will keep you posted.andM;There are two main reasons for the substantial difference in success rates.andO;First, GAO goes into a protest assuming the agency acted properly.andP;  A protestis sustained only when evidence shows otherwise.andP;  The GSBCA, on the otherhand, does not assume either party is correct when reviewing a case.andM;The second reason is that GAO protests are inexpensive compared with GSBCAprotests and encourage full protest resolution instead of settlement.andP;  As GAOchanges its procedures to more closely resemble GSBCA's, I anticipate thedifference will diminish.andM;Bob Dornan is vice president of Federal Sources Inc., Vienna, Va.andO;</TEXT></DOC>